 "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Alveolar macrophages", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8828460574150085, "span": {"begin": 2720, "end": 2740}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001195"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "asbestosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999949932098389, "span": {"begin": 2746, "end": 2756}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9778347015380859, "span": {"begin": 2757, "end": 2765}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011658"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "lung fibrosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999828934669495, "span": {"begin": 2777, "end": 2790}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "alveolar macrophages", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4674718379974365, "span": {"begin": 2851, "end": 2871}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "patients", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9338764548301697, "span": {"begin": 2894, "end": 2902}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011658"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999993443489075, "span": {"begin": 2918, "end": 2947}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1277"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "collagen type I", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9939086437225342, "span": {"begin": 2953, "end": 2968}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6362"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "C-C motif chemokine ligand (CCL)-18", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9734247326850891, "span": {"begin": 3017, "end": 3052}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6347"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CCL-2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9822193384170532, "span": {"begin": 3054, "end": 3059}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD204", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.985991895198822, "span": {"begin": 3064, "end": 3069}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:90865"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IL-33 cytokine", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8655256032943726, "span": {"begin": 3130, "end": 3144}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "M2 macrophages", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.5195401906967163, "span": {"begin": 3170, "end": 3184}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3596"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-13", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9887562394142151, "span": {"begin": 3224, "end": 3229}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7040"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TGF-&beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954304695129395, "span": {"begin": 3234, "end": 3243}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9780770540237427, "span": {"begin": 3249, "end": 3253}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8128594756126404, "span": {"begin": 3313, "end": 3318}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "M2 sub-phenotypes", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.6266389489173889, "span": {"begin": 3335, "end": 3352}}, {"id": ["mim:606963", "mesh:D029424"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "chronic obstructive pulmonary disease", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999990463256836, "span": {"begin": 3407, "end": 3444}}], "text": "Na&iuml;ve CD4+ T cells differentiate into four types of T helper (Th) cells &ndash; Th1, Th2, Th17 and inducible regulatory T cells following exposure to infectious agents. The differentiation process begins when antigen presenting cells (APCs) come in contact with toxic substances and is mainly driven by cytokines that make up the microenvironment. For example, increased concentrations of Interleukin (IL)-12 secreted by APCs in the environment may be biased towards Th1 type and increased IL-6 or IL-4 in the environment may commit to Th2 type differentiation. Th1 cytokines, Interferon gamma (IFN-&gamma;) and IL-12 induce inflammation, aid in clearance of toxic substances, induce tissue damage and control the fibrotic responses. IFN-&gamma;&nbsp;has suppressive effects on the production of extracellular matrix proteins including collagen and fibronectin. The Th2 response suppresses Th1 mediated response, which results in decreased Th1 cell-mediated tissue damage but at the same time contributing to the persistence of toxic substances leading to perpetuation of tissue damage, triggering uncontrolled healing response. The major sources of Th2 cytokines are Th2 cells themselves; however, mast cells, macrophages, epithelial cells and activated fibroblasts have shown to produce IL-4, IL-13 and IL-10 upon appropriate stimulation. Th2 cytokines IL-4 and IL-13 regulate wound healing.  Literature evidence for its perturbation in the context of pulmonary fibrosis:  For fibroplasia or fibrosis, the type of CD4+ T cell response that develops is crucial. Studies conducted in mice that do not express Th2 cytokines IL-4, IL-5 and IL-13 show complete attenuation of fibrosis despite the highly active Th1 response. Th2 cytokines IL-4 and IL-13 are elevated in fibrotic lungs; IL-13 activates Transforming growth factor beta 1 (TGF-&beta;1) and initiates fibroblast proliferation and differentiation in lung fibrosis (Lee et al., 2001). Overexpression of IL-13 induces sub-epithelial airway fibrosis in mice in the absence of any other external pro-inflammatory or pro-fibrotic stimulus (Zhu et al., 1999). Both multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNTs) and single-walled carbon nanotubes induce elevated expression of IL-4 and IL-13 in bronchoalveolar lavage fluid (BALF) of mouse lungs (Park et al., 2011), and increased levels of IL-25 and IL- 33 in BALF and mouse lungs exposed to MWCNTs (Dong and Ma, 2018). In a rare human study, increased levels IL-4 and IL-5 were observed in the sputum of humans exposed to MWCNTs at an occupational setting (Fatkhutdinova et al., 2016). Overexpression of IL-10 increases IL-4 and IL-13 production and lung fibrosis following exposure to silica (Barbarin et al., 2005). Alveolar macrophages from asbestosis patients (a form of lung fibrosis) exhibit M2 phenotype (He et al., 2013). Ex vivo culture of alveolar macrophages obtained from BALF of patients suffering from idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis with collagen type I showed enhanced levels of M2 macrophage markers C-C motif chemokine ligand (CCL)-18, CCL-2 and CD204 (Stahl et al., 2013). Th2 response associated expression of IL-33 cytokine enhances polarisation of M2 macrophages and inducing M2-mediated expression of IL-13 and TGF-&beta;1 in mice (Dong and Ma, 2018). Cigarette smoke induces expression of genes associated with M2 sub-phenotypes, which is further enhanced in smokers presenting with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (Shaykhiev et al., 2009).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:40:55 +0000 2026"}